<!-- Section 1 of Women in STEM -->
<section id="overview">
  <div id="slide2" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent wrapper">
        <div id="define">
          <span class="firstL">S</span><span>cience</span><br>
          <span class="firstL">T</span><span>echnology</span><br>
          <span class="firstL">E</span><span>ngineering</span><br>
          <span class="firstL">M</span><span>athematics</span>
        </div>
        <div class="column">
          <i class="fa fa-laptop fa-2x" aria-hidden="true"></i> <br>
          <i class="fa fa-heartbeat fa-2x" aria-hidden="true"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="column">
          <i class="fa fa-rocket fa-2x" aria-hidden="true"></i> <br>
          <i class="fa fa-superscript fa-2x" aria-hidden="true"></i>
        </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="slide3" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>Despite growth and accessibility for education and career options, there are still societal and cultural barriers against women in STEM.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="slide4" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>No region in the world has been able to reach <span class="stat">50%</span> representation of women in STEM.</p>
      <p class="source">http://www.catalyst.org/knowledge/women-science-technology-engineering-and-mathematics-stem</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="slide5" class="parallax">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>"Society keeps telling us that STEM fields are masculine fields, that we need to
        increase the participation of women in STEM fields, but that kind of sends a signal that
        it’s not a field for women, and it kind of works against keeping women in these fields.”<br>
        <em>Adriana D. Kugler</em></p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/08/29/study-says-multiple-factors-work-together-drive-women-away-stem</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide6" class="slides">
    <i class="fa fa-male fa-4x" aria-hidden="true"></i>
    <i class="fa fa-male fa-4x" aria-hidden="true"></i>
    <i class="fa fa-male fa-4x" aria-hidden="true"></i>
    <i class="fa fa-female fa-4x" aria-hidden="true" id="woman"></i>
    <p>Less than 1/4 of STEM jobs are held by women</p>
    <p class="source">Solving for XX</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide7" class="slides">
   <div class="innerContent" >
     <h3>In 2013, only a handful of regions averaged had women represent over 1/3 of those employed in scientific research &amp; development.</h3>
     <div class="wrapper">
       <div class="column">
         <p class="count">47.1</p><span>%</span>
         <p>Central Asia</p>
       </div>
       <div class="column">
         <p class="count">44.3</p><span>%</span>
         <p>Latin American &amp; the Caribbean</p>
       </div>
       <div class="column">
         <p class="count">39.9</p><span>%</span>
         <p>Central &amp; Eastern Europe</p>
       </div>
       <div class="column">
         <p class="count">36.8</p><span>%</span>
         <p>Arab States</p>
       </div>
     </div>
   </div>
   <p class="source">http://www.catalyst.org/knowledge/women-science-technology-engineering-and-mathematics-stem</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide8" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>"People ask me all the time: 'What is it like to be a woman at Google?' I'm not a woman at Google, I'm a geek at Google. And being a geek is just great." <br>
      <em>Marissa Mayer</em></p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="slide9" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>In the United States, 38% of women quit engineering or never enter the professional field after recieveing a degree.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">http://www.catalyst.org/knowledge/women-science-technology-engineering-and-mathematics-stem</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide10" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>In a study, many female engineers cited poor pay &amp; promotional opportunities as reasons for leaving.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/04/what-does-the-stem-gender-breakdown-really-look-like/</p>
  </div>
</section>
<!-- Section 2 of Women in STEM -->
<section id="international">
  <div id="slide11" class="parallax">
     <p class="quote">"For too long, discriminatory stereotypes have prevented women and girls from
       having equal access to education in science, technology, engineering and math (STEM).
       As a trained engineer and former teacher, I know that these stereotypes are flat wrong.
       They deny women and girls the chance to realize their potential—and deprive the world of
       the ingenuity and innovation of half the population."<br>
       <em>United Nations Secretary-General, Mr. Antonio Guterres</em></p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide12" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>Around the world women are using technology to break the glass ceiling</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="slide13" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>In Brazil, China, India, and the US, 80-93% of women in STEM say they <span class="highLight">love</span> their work.</p>
      <p>So why will 20-32% of them quit within a year?</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/04/what-does-the-stem-gender-breakdown-really-look-like/</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide14" class="parallax">
     <p class="quote">"For too long, discriminatory stereotypes have prevented women and girls from
       having equal access to education in science, technology, engineering and math (STEM).
       As a trained engineer and former teacher, I know that these stereotypes are flat wrong.
       They deny women and girls the chance to realize their potential—and deprive the world of
       the ingenuity and innovation of half the population."<br>
       <em>United Nations Secretary-General, Mr. Antonio Guterres</em></p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide15" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <h3>International: Men Outnumber Women in STEM</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Australia: Less than 1/6 students enrolled in STEM fields were women</li>
        <li>Canada: Women represent over half in physical and life science technology fields, but between 19-25.4% in STEM.</li>
        <li>India: The country has almost 50% reached gender equity in science majors, but has between 28.1-44% for Engineering and Technology.</li>
        <li>France: One of the stronger countries in the EU-28 France's gender gap in STEM is 25.6%</li>
        <li>Switzerland: Near the bottom of the list for EU-28 countries, is Switzerland at 14.7%</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <p class="source">http://www.catalyst.org/knowledge/women-science-technology-engineering-and-mathematics-stem</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide16" class="parallax">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>"Our society is inching toward a future when the phrase 'you code like a girl' will be a compliment of the highest order."<br>
      <em>Stephanie Walden</em></p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">http://mashable.com/2016/01/22/women-in-stem-global/#r88R.76r_uqX</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide17" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>In Malaysia, the National Association of Women Entrepreneurs of Malaysia (NAWEM) unites female entrepreneurs in STEM, providing mentorship opportunities, networking, and conferences.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">http://mashable.com/2016/01/22/women-in-stem-global/#r88R.76r_uqX</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide18" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>Indian Girls Code, is a free program from Robotix, focusing on getting girls from underprivileged backgrounds involved in and excited about computer science &amp; technology.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">http://mashable.com/2016/01/22/women-in-stem-global/#r88R.76r_uqX</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide19" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>Through annual awards, the European Ada Awards recognizes women in technology, such as 'Digital Girl of the Year' &amp; 'Digital Woman of the Year'.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">http://mashable.com/2016/01/22/women-in-stem-global/#r88R.76r_uqX</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide20" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <div class="wrapper">
        <div class="column">
          
          <h3><a href="http://www.un.org/en/events/women-and-girls-in-science-day/">United Nations International Day</a> of Women &amp; Girls in Science</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="column">
          <p>Adopted to help achieve gender equality, empowerment, access &amp; participation of women and girls in STEM</p>
        </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="slide21" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>Johnson &amp; Johnson is dedicated to supporting women in STEM through the WiSTEM2D (Women in Science, Technology, Engineering, Math, Manufacturing and Design) Scholars Program in Japan, Brazil, Ireland &amp; the US.</p>
      <p>Through this program Johnson &amp; Johnson aims to mentor the next generation of STEM leaders, and increase the group of qualified women who can work on innovation, big data, and AI - hopefully at their company.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">https://www.jnj.com/innovation/how-johnson-and-johnson-supports-women-in-stem-around-the-world</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide22" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>UNESCO works with L'Oreal to offer support and recognition for the work of women in STEM fields.</p>
      <p>In regions where women are especially underrepresented, such as the Middle East and Sub-Saharan Africa, L'Oreal offers fellowships to promising young women in STEM.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">http://www.unesco.org/new/en/natural-sciences/priority-areas/gender-and-science/for-women-in-science-programme/</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide23" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <p>In some countries, women in STEM is a larger issue of equal access to education. In developing nations, 110 million children are out of school with 60% being girls.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="source">https://www.elitedaily.com/women/separate-unequal-countries-worst-gender-inequality-education</p>
  </div>
  <div id="slide24" class="slides">
    <div class="innerContent">
      <div class="wrapper">
        <div class="column">
          <p>Making accomplished women scientists visible is important for history, changing biases, building further scientific success &amp; inspiring future generations to get involved in STEM.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="column">
          <img> HIDDEN FIGURES
        </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
